This is doing far too much. This should be broken down into smaller functions that each can be tested and verified.

This class only overrides one method (toString), so it's not that problem. This is saying that it's bad to extend a class but then not use most of its base class internals, and I disagree with that. This class specifically looks like it's a true extension of the base class, and just trusts the uses for the base class to do its job without interfering.

It's definitely not too long. It _might_ be doing too much, but at the end of the day, this is pretty clean to me: It initializes the script runner, executes a particular script, and then returns the evaluated value.

I do think that this class could be broken into a few different classes, or at least have some of the configuration be done in separate classes, but at the end of the day this class does just have one, singular responsibility (to search a directory), so it can hardly be called a god class.

I don't understand the analysis here at all, honestly; this is a very specific class doing a specific thing, with one instance variable and three methods. It's possible the parent class is massive and is a god class, but I can't see that here.
